sano\n|C\n|[[Nazareth Area High School|Nazareth High School]]\n|Yes\n|1988\u20131989\n|Rookie\n|-\n|18\n|Coleman Smith\n|OF\n| [[Conestoga Valley High School]]\n|No <br>[[Chicago Cubs|Cubs]]-1992\n|  1992\u20131994\n|  A\n|-\n|19\n|James Wray\n|LHP\n|[[Troy University]]\n|Yes\n|1988\u20131996\n|AA\n|-\n|20\n|Sean McKamie\n|SS\n|[[St. Paul Central High School]]\n|Yes\n|1989\u20131997\n|  AA\n|-\n|21\n|Steven Finken\n|SS\n|[[University of Michigan]]\n|Yes\n| 1988\u20131992\n|  AAA\n|-\n|22\n|Michael St. Esteben\n|LHP\n|[[Chino High School]]\n|No\n| \n| \n|-\n|23\n|William Wengert\n|RHP\n|[[Iowa State University]]\n|Yes\n|1988\u20131995\n| AAA\n|-\n|24\n|Roderick Harvell\n|OF\n| [[Fairfield, California|Fairfield High School]]\n|Yes\n|1988\u20131989\n|Rookie\n|-\n|25\n|Michael Sampson\n|RHP\n| [[Holyoke Community College]]\n|Yes\n| 1988\u20131991\n| A+\n|-\n|26\n|Ernest Carr\n|3B\n|  [[Jacksonville University]]\n|Yes\n| 1988\u20131990\n|A\n|-\n|27\n|Mike Munson\n|RHP\n| [[University of Illinois at Urbana\u2013Champaign]]\n|No\n|  \n| \n|-\n|28\n|Eric Ganino\n|C\n| [[Fontana High School]]\n|Yes\n|  1988\u20131989\n|Rookie\n|-\n|29\n|John Braase\n|RHP\n| [[College of Idaho]]\n|Yes\n| 1988\u20131990\n|A+\n|-\n|30\n|Sean Snedeker\n|RHP\n| [[Texas A&M University]]\n|Yes\n|  1988\u20131993\n| AA\n|-\n|31\n|Clayton Enno\n|LHP\n| [[Des Moines Area Community College]]\n|Yes\n| 1988\u20131990\n| A+\n|-\n|32\n|Bryan Beals\n|2B\n| [[Chapman University]]\n|Yes\n| 1988\u20131990\n|A+\n|-\n|33\n|Cameron Biberdorf\n|RHP\n| [[Mayville State University]]\n|Yes \n|  1988\u20131991\n| AA\n|-\n|34\n|Napoleon Robinson\n|RHP\n| [[Columbus State University]]\n|Yes\n| 1988\u20131993\n|AAA\n|-\n|35\n|[[H\u00e9ctor Ortiz (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Ortiz]]\n|C\n| [[Ranger College]]\n|Yes\n| 1988\u20132005\n|'''MLB'''\n|-\n|36\n|Jeff Castillo\n|RHP\n| [[Mesa State College]]\n|Yes\n| 1988\n|Rookie\n|-\n|37\n|Bradley Boggetto\n|RHP\n| [[Parkland College]]\n|Yes\n|  1989\u20131991\n| A-\n|-\n|38\n|Wendell Zink\n|3B\n| [[Dixie State College of Utah]]\n|Yes \n| 1988\n| A-\n|-\n|39\n|K. G. White\n|OF\n| [[Georgia Institute of Technology]]\n|Yes\n|1988\u20131989\n|A\n|-\n|40\n|Felix Rios\n|3B\n| [[George Fox University]]\n|No \n|  \n| \n|-\n|41\n|Todd Reische\n|C\n| [[Minooka High School]]\n|No \n|  \n| \n|-\n|42\n|Eric Blackwell\n|OF\n| [[Spartanburg Methodist College]]\n|Yes\n| 1989\u20131991\n|A+\n|-\n|43\n|[[Garey Ingram]]\n|C\n| [[Columbus High School (Columbus, Georgia)|Columbus High School]]\n|No<br>[[Los Angeles Dodgers|Dodgers]]-1989\n| 1990\u20132002\n|'''MLB'''\n|-\n|44\n|Brent Miller\n|3B\n| [[Muscogee County School District|Jordan High School]]\n|No<br>[[Baltimore Orioles|Orioles]]-1990\n| 1990\u20131994\n|AAA\n|-\n|45\n|Bradley Cohen\n|OF\n| [[Starkville High School]]\n|No \n| \n| \n|-\n|46\n|Wilfred Brown\n|SS\n| [[Lurleen B. Wallace Community College]]\n|No\n|  \n| \n|-\n|47\n|Garrett Beard\n|OF\n| [[Spartanburg Methodist College]]\n|Yes\n|1989\u20131995\n|AAA\n|-\n|48\n|Terry Miller\n|OF\n| [[Compton Community College]]\n|No \n| \n| \n|-\n|49\n|Deon Montgomery\n|SS\n| [[Compton Community College]]\n|No \n|  \n| \n|-\n|50\n|Jose Fernandez\n|OF\n| [[City College of San Francisco]]\n|No \n| \n| \n|-\n|51\n|Daniel Hancock\n|RHP\n| [[Bremen High School (Midlothian, Illinois)|Bremen High School]]\n|No \n| \n| \n|-\n|52\n|Gaither Bagsby\n|RHP\n| [[Dickson County, Tennessee|Dickson County High School]]\n|No \n| \n|\n|-\n|53\n|Michael Emmons\n|RHP\n| [[Pensacola Junior College]]\n|No \n| \n|\n|-\n|54\n|Shannon Zerlang\n|OF\n| [[College of the Redwoods]]\n|No \n| \n|\n|-\n|55\n|Craig Thomas\n|OF\n| [[Northside High School (Warner Robins, Georgia)|Northside High School]]\n|No \n| \n|\n|-\n|56\n|Dan Frye\n|SS\n| [[Logansport, Indiana|Logansport High School]]\n|No <br>[[Cincinnati Reds|Reds]]-1992\n| 1992\u20131995\n|A+\n|-\n|57\n|Dennis Frye\n|1B\n| [[Logansport, Indiana|Logansport High School]]\n|No \n| \n|\n|-\n|58\n|Mike Vdovkin\n|RHP\n| [[Merced High School]]\n|No \n| \n|\n|-\n|59\n|Chris Harding\n|OF\n| [[Louisburg College]]\n|No \n| \n|\n|-\n|60\n|Robert Hoffman\n|C\n| [[John F. Kennedy High School (Richmond, California)|J. F. Kennedy High School]]\n|No <br>[[Los Angeles Dodgers|Dodgers]]-1989\n| 1990\n|Rookie\n|-\n|61\n|Eric Boddie\n|OF\n| [[Creighton University]]\n|Yes\n| 1988\u20131990\n|A+\n|-\n|62\n|[[Mike Piazza]]\n|1B\n| [[Miami Dade College]]\n|Yes\n| 1989\u20132007\n|'''MLB'''\n|}\n\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Orel Hershiser's scoreless innings streak]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://exhibits.baseballhalloffame.org/dressed_to_the_nines/detail_page.asp?fileName=nl_1988_losangeles.gif&Entryid=1616 1988 Los Angeles Dodgers uniform]\n*[http://www.Dodgers.com Los Angeles Dodgers official web site]\n*[https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/LAD/1988.shtml Baseball-Reference season page]\n*[http://www.baseball-almanac.com/teamstats/roster.php?y=1988&t=LAN Baseball Almanac season page]\n\n{{World Series champions}}\n{{National League champions}}\n{{National League West champions}}\n{{1988 MLB season by team}}\n{{1988 Los Angeles Dodgers}}\n{{Los Angeles Dodgers}}\n\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers seasons]]\n[[Category:1988 Major League Baseball season|Los Angeles Dodgers]]\n[[Category:National League West champion seasons]]\n[[Category:National League champion seasons]]\n[[Category:World Series champion seasons]]\n[[Category:1988 in sports in California|Los Angeles Dodgers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toZane Smith(link changed toZane Smith (baseball); link changed toZane Smith (baseball); link changed toZane Smith (baseball)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1988_Los_Angeles_Dodgers_season"}
{"title_page": "1990 Cincinnati Reds season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox MLB yearly\n| name = Cincinnati Reds\n| season = 1990\n| misc = 1990 NL West Champions<br>1990 NL Champions<br>[[1990 World Series]] Champions\n| logo = \n| current league = National League\n| y1 =  1890\n| Uniform logo = \n| division = National League West\n| y2 = 1969\n| ballpark = [[Riverfront Stadium]]\n| y4 = 1970\n| city = [[Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]]\n| y5 = 1882\n| record = 91\u201371 (.562)\n| divisional place = 1st\n| owners = [[Marge Schott]]\n| general managers = [[Bob Quinn (baseball grandson)|Bob Quinn]]\n| managers = [[Lou Piniella]]\n| television = [[WLWT]] <br>([[Johnny Bench]], [[Tom Hume]], Steve LaMar, [[Gordy Coleman]])\n| radio =  [[WLW]]<br>([[Marty Brennaman]], [[Joe Nuxhall]])\n|}}\n\nThe '''[[Cincinnati Reds]]' [[1990 in baseball|1990 season]]''' was the Reds' 122nd season in American [[baseball]]. Starting with a club best nine straight wins to open the season, as well as holding the top spot in the National League West every game during the season, the Reds went 41-21 after 62 games, splitting the remaining 100 games 50-50 to end up with a 91-71 record. It consisted of the 91-71 Reds winning the [[National League West]] by five games over the second-place [[1990 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Dodgers]], as well as the [[National League Championship Series]] in six games over the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], and the [[World Series]] in a four-game sweep over the overwhelming favorite [[Oakland Athletics]], who had won the World Series the previous year.  It was the fifth [[World Series|World Championship]] for the [[Cincinnati Reds|Reds]], and their first since winning two consecutive titles in [[1975 World Series|1975]] and '[[1976 World Series|76]].\n\n==Offseason==\n* December 6, 1989: [[John Franco]] and Don Brown (minors) were traded by the Reds to the [[New York Mets]] for [[Randy Myers]] and [[Kip Gross]].<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/m/myersra01.shtml Randy Myers] at ''Baseball Reference''</ref>\n* December 12, 1989: [[Tim Leary (baseball)|Tim Leary]] and [[Van Snider]] were traded by the Reds to the [[New York Yankees]] for [[Hal Morris]] and Rodney Imes (minors).<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/l/learyti01.shtml Tim Leary] at ''Baseball Reference''</ref>\n\n==Regular season==\n[[Image:Eric davis.jpg|thumb|right|225px|[[Eric Davis (baseball)|Eric Davis]] in 1990]]\nLed by new manager [[Lou Piniella]], the Reds achieved the rare feat of being in first place everyday of the season (\"wire-to-wire\").<ref name=\"Great Baseball Feats p.366\">''Great Baseball Feats, Facts and Figures'', 2008 Edition, p.366, David Nemec and Scott Flatow, A Signet Book, Penguin Group, New York, {{ISBN|978-0-451-22363-0}}</ref> They also became the first [[National League]] team to do so.<ref name=\"CE09-30-1990pg1\">{{cite news|title=Wire to Wire!|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34822711/|first=Jack|last=Brennan|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|date=September 30, 1990|accessdate=August 12, 2019}}{{Open access}}</ref> Starting pitcher [[Jack Armstrong (baseball)|Jack Armstrong]] was a catalyst for the team's fast start, as he won 8 of his first 9 games and was 11-3 through the All Star break.  Because of his strong first half, Armstrong was selected as the starting pitcher for the All Star Game.\n\nThe Reds clinched the NL West division on Saturday September 29 in a rain-shortened, seven-inning 3-1 home loss to San Diego. The second-place [[1990 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Dodgers]] lost to the [[1990 San Francisco Giants season|Giants]] at the same time, mathematically clinching the division for Cincinnati with four games remaining.<ref name=\"CE09-30-1990pg1\"/>\n\n===Opening Day===\nDue to the [[1990 Major League Baseball lockout|1990 lockout]], [[Opening Day]] was pushed back one week from April 2 to April 9. As a result, the Reds who traditionally started every major league season with the first pitch at home on opening day, were forced to start on the road.<ref>{{cite news|title=Astros take Reds out to Opening Day (Part 1)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/30376624/|first=John|last=Fay|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|date=April 9, 1990|accessdate=August 12, 2019}}{{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Astros take Reds out to Opening Day (Part 2)|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34821531/|first=John|last=Fay|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|date=April 9, 1990|accessdate=August 12, 2019}}{{Open access}}</ref> The Reds played three games at [[1990 Houston Astros season|Houston]] and three games at [[1990 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta]] before returning for their home opener on Tuesday April 17. It was only the third time since 1876 that the Reds opened the season with an away game. The traditional [[Findlay Market]] parade, along with other customary opening day festivities, were held off until April 17 and rebranded \"Reds Homecomming.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34822129/|title=Red-hot Reds welcomed back (Part 1)|first=John|last=Fay|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|date=April 17, 1990|accessdate=August 12, 2019}}{{Open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34822077/|title=Red-hot Reds welcomed back (Part 2)|first=John|last=Fay|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|page=14|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|date=April 17, 1990|accessdate=August 12, 2019}}{{Open access}}</ref> On a chilly 49\u00b0 afternoon, the 6\u20130 Reds beat [[1990 San Diego Padres season|San Diego]] in front of a crowd of 38,384 at [[Riverfront Stadium]] - small for opening day standards - to improve to 7\u20130 on the season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reds victory closes perfect opener|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/34822285/|first=John|last=Fay|newspaper=The Cincinnati Enquirer|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|date=April 18, 1990|accessdate=August 12, 2019}}{{Open access}}</ref>\n\n===1990 Major League Baseball All-Star Game===\n{{main article|1990 Major League Baseball All-Star Game}}\nCincinnati was well represented at the 1990 All-Star Game in [[Wrigley Field|Chicago]]. In addition to Armstrong at pitcher, [[Chris Sabo]], [[Barry Larkin]], [[Rob Dibble]], and [[Randy Myers]] were reserves.\n\n===The Nasty Boys===\nAnother new face in the Reds locker room was [[Randy Myers]]. He was acquired from the New York Mets for closer [[John Franco]], and became part of the '''[[Nasty Boys (Cincinnati Reds)|Nasty Boys]]''', along with [[Rob Dibble]] and [[Norm Charlton]]. Charlton, Dibble, and Myers combined for 44 saves (Myers with 31, Dibble with 11, and Charlton with 2). Myers would become one of the league's elite closers while being selected as an All-Star in 1990. Myers would win his second World Championship as the Reds swept the Oakland Athletics.\n\n: ''\"The Nasty Boys \u2014 The Reds' three flame-throwing relievers, Randy Myers, [[Rob Dibble]] and [[Norm Charlton]], emerged as arguably the deepest and most talented late-inning pitchers in postseason history.\"'' &mdash; John Erardi and John Fay, [[Cincinnati Enquirer|The Cincinnati Enquirer]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://reds.enquirer.com/2002/06/23/red_surprise_90_series.html |title=Surprise '90 Series sweep of A's defined team effort |publisher=Reds.enquirer.com |accessdate=August 24, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414112259/http://reds.enquirer.com/2002/06/23/red_surprise_90_series.html |archive-date=April 14, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Season standings===\n{{1990 NL West standings|highlight=Cincinnati Reds}}\n\n===Record vs. opponents===\n{{1990 NL Record vs. opponents|team=CIN}}\n\n===Notable transactions===\n* June 4, 1990: [[1990 Major League Baseball draft]]\n**[[Dan Wilson (baseball)|Dan Wilson]] was drafted by the Reds in the 1st round.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/draft/?year_ID=1990&round=1&draft_type=junreg Baseball Draft: 1st Round of the 1990 June Draft] ''Baseball-Reference.com''</ref>\n**[[John Roper (baseball)|John Roper]] was drafted by the Reds in the 12th round.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/r/roperjo01.shtml John Roper] at ''Baseball Reference''</ref>\n*June 9, 1990: Ron Robinson was traded by the Cincinnati Reds with [[Bob Sebra]] to the Milwaukee Brewers for [[Billy Bates (baseball)|Billy Bates]] and [[Glenn Braggs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/robinro01.shtml |title=Ron Robinson Statistics and History |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref>\n*June 18, 1990: Rolando Roomes was selected off waivers by the Montreal Expos from the Cincinnati Reds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/r/roomero01.shtml |title=Rolando Roomes Statistics and History |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref>\n* August 24, 1990: [[Ken Griffey, Sr.]] was released by the Reds.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/g/griffke01.shtml Ken Griffey] at ''Baseball Reference''</ref>\n* August 30, 1990: Bill Doran was traded by the Houston Astros to the Cincinnati Reds for players to be named later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/d/doranbi02.shtml |title=Bill Doran Statistics and History |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref>\n* September 7, 1990: Butch Henry was sent by the Cincinnati Reds to the Houston Astros to complete an earlier deal made on August 30, 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/h/henrybu01.shtml |title=Butch Henry Statistics and History |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref> Catcher Terry McGriff was also sent by the Cincinnati Reds to complete the deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/m/mcgrite01.shtml |title=Terry McGriff Statistics and History |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Roster===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" style=\"background:#c6011f; color:#fff; text-align:center;\"| 1990 Cincinnati Reds \n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"background:black; color:#fff; text-align:center;\"| '''Roster'''\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" | '''Pitchers'''\n{{MLBplayer|40|[[Jack Armstrong (baseball)|Jack Armstrong]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|48|[[Tim Birtsas]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|38|[[Keith Brown (baseball)|Keith Brown]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|32|[[Tom Browning]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|37|[[Norm Charlton]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|49|[[Rob Dibble]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|59|[[Kip Gross]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|45|[[Chris Hammond]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|20|[[Danny Jackson]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|43|[[Tim Layana]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|42|[[Rick Mahler]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|33|[[Gino Minutelli]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|28|[[Randy Myers]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|27|[[Jos\u00e9 Rijo]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|33|[[Ron Robinson (baseball)|Ron Robinson]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|56|[[Rosario Rodr\u00edguez]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|47|[[Scott Scudder]]}}\n| style=\"width:25px;\"| \n| valign=\"top\" | '''Catchers'''\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;8|[[Terry McGriff]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;9|[[Joe Oliver (baseball)|Joe Oliver]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|34|[[Jeff Reed (baseball)|Jeff Reed]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|55|[[Glenn Sutko]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;8|[[Alex Trevi\u00f1o]]}}\n'''Infielders'''\n{{MLBplayer|12|[[Billy Bates (baseball)|Billy Bates]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|25|[[Todd Benzinger]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|19|[[Bill Doran (baseball)|Bill Doran]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;7|[[Mariano Duncan]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|30|[[Ken Griffey, Sr.|Ken Griffey]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|11|[[Barry Larkin]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|26|[[Terry Lee (baseball)|Terry Lee]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|23|[[Hal Morris]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|16|[[Ron Oester]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|10|[[Luis Qui\u00f1ones]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|17|[[Chris Sabo]]}}\n| style=\"width:25px;\"| \n| valign=\"top\" | '''Outfielders'''\n{{MLBplayer|15|[[Glenn Braggs]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|44|[[Eric Davis (baseball)|Eric Davis]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|22|[[Billy Hatcher]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|21|[[Paul O'Neill (baseball)|Paul O'Neill]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|36|[[Rolando Roomes]]}}\n{{MLBplayer|29|[[Herm Winningham]]}}\n'''Other batters'''\n{{MLBplayer|12|[[Paul Noce]]}}\n| style=\"width:25px;\"| \n| valign=\"top\" | '''Manager'''\n{{MLBplayer|41|[[Lou Piniella]]}}\n'''Coaches'''\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;4|[[Jackie Moore (baseball)|Jackie Moore]]}} (Bench)\n{{MLBplayer|24|[[Tony P\u00e9rez]]}} (Hitting/First Base)\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;2|[[Sam Perlozzo]]}} (Third Base)\n{{MLBplayer|&nbsp;3|[[Larry Rothschild]]}} (Bullpen)\n{{MLBplayer|35|[[Stan Williams (baseball)|Stan Williams]]}} (Pitching)\n\n|}\n\n===Opening Day starters===\n* [[Todd Benzinger]], First Base\n* [[Mariano Duncan]], Second Base\n* [[Chris Sabo]], Third Base\n* [[Barry Larkin]], Shortstop\n* [[Joe Oliver (baseball)|Joe Oliver]], Catcher\n* [[Billy Hatcher]], Left field\n* [[Eric Davis (baseball)|Eric Davis]], Center field\n* [[Paul O'Neill (baseball)|Paul O'Neill]], Right field\n* [[Tom Browning]], Pitcher\n\n==Player stats==\n{|\n|-\n| style=\"background:#fc0; border:1px solid #aaa; width:2em;\"|\n| = Indicates team leader\n|}\n\n===Batting===\n\n====Starters by position====\n''Note: Pos = Position; G = Games played; AB = At bats; H = Hits; Avg. = Batting average; HR = Home runs; RBI = Runs batted in''\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:black; color:#d40026; width:5%;\"| Pos\n!  style=\"background:black; color:#d40026; width:16%;\"| Player\n!  style=\"background:black; color:#d40026; width:9%;\"| G\n!  style=\"background:black; color:#d40026; width:9%;\"| AB\n!  style=\"background:black; color:#d40026; width:9%;\"| H\n!  style=\"background:black; color:#d40026; width:9%;\"| Avg.\n!  style=\"background:black; color:#d40026; width:9%;\"| HR\n!  style=\"background:black; color:#d40026; width:9%;\"| RBI\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| C || {{sortname|Joe|Oliver|Joe Oliver (baseball)}} || 121 || 364 || 84 || .231 || 8 